Nat depends I mean I'm I - I remember when I went to school until I left school 
I had to go all the way from Rathbone Road there to Kensington to the Maypole 'cos if you remember they used to - give you double weight on the margarine, you remember, if it was sixpence a pound you got two pound for sixpence and I had to walk all the wa
y
 to Kensington for that. But - as - as the other shop, no, excepting say if we wanted a pair or boots or a pair of shoes like me father would take you for them you see because he knew what he wanted you see, he didn't - and we went to - we went to Kensing
t
on one time to Freeman Hardy and Weillis and he said to the man in the shop, show me a pair of lads boots will you? You know, what it say - saying what he wanted. Box calves and so the fellow gave him a pair of boots and he said, I don't want that rubbish
. The fellow said, oh, it's a wonderful - you know. He said, look, he said, I worked for Freeman he said, before your father was born, he said, don't tell me. And I got the finest pair of shoes I ever had.
