Oh of course I was in the Boys Brigade you see and of course we used to have a lot of - things, you see. Three nights we'd get in the Boys Brigade like one nigh
t was your drill night and that was for discipline you see. The other night was gymans - gymnastics and then other night like we used to - used to have a little billiard; table in a little room, little - only little you know - about as big as this. And th
e
n I - I used to - also from the Sunday school we used to organize - an - another old lady in - in the church used to organize concerts you know and I remember - when the first world war broke out we went around, oh many of these places in Liverpool her an
d
 - and I remember I played the part of the - the villain or the Baron in - Maid Marion and - Robin Hood. And - in them days like you know the echo used to report these things much better than they do now and we got a wonderful write up about that particul
a
rly like I did - I did because I had a laughing song to sing which was you know, pretty difficult to sing, you know, ha, ha, ha, ha, ha, ha, ha, all through the song you see. And - I suppose I got that because of - probably be the oldest of the - of the S
unday school people that time and they had the deeper voice you see at the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you belong to a choir?
