 then I was learning to take tenor parts you see. The organist at that time was - Herbert E Kinsey - you'll find many of his tunes in the hymn book today. He was a German but he was a wonderful man and he was - he - I do know that the fees that he receive
d
 from St Mary's he gave back because he was a voice production specialist and later on in life when I got into the leading four we used to attend his house every Saturday morning for - music lessons and - in voice production, that, you know. We used to lo
v
e it as kids. The maid would give us tea and biscuits until he got up and shaved and came down to the music room and then we'd have our lesson 'til about twelve o'clock on the Saturday. Well this, like this went on - all the time - as I say until about 19
1
5. We used to have - we got paid for it according to your height - I suppose the top lad got about ten bob a quarter and it goes down to - I think you started at about half a crown. Then at Harvest Festival time the Rector would give you - perhaps some ap
