- she'll tell you now that she was always struck by the way - it didn't matter where you looked, there was sewing you know. The dresser would be full of it. You wouldn't see anything for sewing - she'd be doing something for somebody and of course when th
e
 war came on you know it used to be - somebody wanted a shirt, take it to Cassie, that was me mother see, she'll run it up for you in no time and - like then like at the church they wanted to form a sewing circle it was me mother that - they got to show t
h
em how to make shirts and cut them out and sew them up and - and the first overalls that we had here at Crawfords me mother made them out of flour bags. I - and even when I came home out of the Army Miss - Mrs. - Mrs Jackson would say, will you take these
 
flour bags up to your mother? She wanted a dozen overalls. She was - and - and me eldest sister when - when she left school like see, just about that time they started evening schools if you remember and she went to the evening schools at Birchfield Road 
here for cookery and needlework and she won everything that there was in - to offer, and she went to Wavertree Technical school.
