ll you go then. And I said, oh well I'm looking out for something. And she said to me, would you like to go to Crawfords? And I said, oh very much, if I could get in. She said, well I'll speak to Mr McCulloch. And so - at the end of the week she said to m
e
 - on Monday will you go to Crawfords and ask for Mr Owen and tell him that you're the boy that Mr - Mr Mculloch spoke to him about and I remember this Monday I went up to Crawfords and there was quite a queue you know of - Boys. And Mr Owen said, no more
 today, no more. And so I - went into him, I said - I'm - I'm the boy that Mr McCulloch spoke to you about. He said, oh, come in, he said. Now - I can only offer you a job in Mr McCullochs department in - in the bakehouse. I said, well that }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11798229\charrsid3029110 wi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 ll suit me ver
y - very nicely like if you could do - try it anyway. So that's how I started at Crawfords in 1912.
