\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Going there would be entirely different from working for a person that you knew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Oh yes - oh definitely, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 How did the change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Well - at first it was a bit strange you know and - and - see I wa
s only a little chap Never - never at any time did I scale any weight. And of course - things were a little difficult especially - it was pretty hard work at the time - lifting big tins of scrap and of course you some great man who sort of you know, liked
 
to be funny and would push the weight on you, you see, them being taller - give you the heavy end. But I didn't complain and then - and it went on very well until - I'd been there perhaps - oh perhaps eighteen months or so - about fifteen months I think a
n
d Mr MckCucloch moved me from the machine I was on - onto the machine that his son, Jimmy, ran. Well - because there'd been a bit of trouble at two lads - they'd been fighting and he'd had to sack one lad. And so he came into this machine that I was on an
d
 told me to go into number nine machine which was the first one then in the new - what we called the new extension - and put me on the machine with Jimmy. And there I got on like very well with him. Yes - and eventually like he moved me up from - working 
pans to dough feeding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 How did you feel about the work - did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Oh yes, yes. 'Cos it was interesting it was machinery and it was - confection, you see, it was working with live dough wasn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did the job alter your attitude to school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
To school? Oh - always of course and - and like particularly the set - the class of people I've moved into in my - spare time always gave me the - feeling that I'd been robbed of a little bit - the lack of the scholarships in the school you se
e, because all the chaps that I've met with had gone to - board schools, you know, which were a little higher than the - and they'd had chances better than me, they'd taken them and they were - they were all going to night school which of course I - I thr
ew up because of it - it interfered with my Boys Brigade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 What jobs did you do since the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Nothing - only Crawfords.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 But you've done different jobs there haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Always in machine room. Always on a machine. When - w
hen I was - when the war broke out in 1914 you see, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4087616\charrsid3029110 several}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
- men being in the volun - in - in - the Territorials then had immediately to join up. That left of course - a lot of space in - you see in the set up and Mr McCulloch came to me one Friday and he 
said to me, you see, with - with Jimmy I'd learnt an awful lot about the machines and in many cases you know you got some hard cases of lads at work and they used to do terrible things if the boss just happened to be away for a moment and I'd learnt to ge
t
 things going very often before he came back and - get them out of trouble and he came to me this day and said, I'm going to put you - on number eleven - machine on Monday, he said, but he said, I don't want you, he said, to say anything to anybody until 
t
hey see you on the job on - on Monday morning because of course, he said, you're only young and you haven't been here so long as some of these chaps and they'll be bit resentful at me moving you up, you see, until you show that you can do it. So - and tha
t
 was in 1914, you see, I became a machine man. Yes. That's two years after I started there Just over. Yes, I became a machine man - and I was machine man you see - then the war of course got a bit more complicated and they were beginning to call people up
.
 And this Lord Derby scheme came on and my pal said to me, how about joining the Army? See, so - I said to me father, Joe wants to join, how about - can I? And he said, no. He said, I wouldn't mind if - it was really necessary but, he said, at present he 
s
aid, there's too many fellows hanging round the street corners, lounging around doing nothing, he said, you've got a steady job - stay at it until you've got to go. Well that went on for - for a few months more and until things were getting pretty bad and
 he said to me, now, you can please yourself about joining the Army, he said, I wouldn't like to see you - conscripted - forced to go in, you see. So we joined the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 When would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 1915. And I - we went around town looking for a place be
cause - at that time our senior officers in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 How old would you be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
About nineteen then. Yes. Our senior officers in the Boys Brigade had been conscripted but they were - they'd joined the Army most of them - Captain A.S. Evans he was the - Cont
inental Secrary of the Cunard liners, he was very - very nice gentleman and they'd gone and we were in the drill competition at the Scottish Head quarters in Liverpool and as a result my - may pal and I, we were Staff Sergeants, we had to take company com
m
and - our companies you see and - I just forget how we went on - I don't think we won it but we were - we were pretty near and - some chap offered us Corporal stripes in the Army if we joined the Army you see. So - we went round town and - you know, these
 recruiting Sergeants, one said to my pal, come on, in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lancashire{\*\xmlclose} and Cheshires for seven years you know so we ran. We went back to Coopers later on and we joined the 21}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
 Lancs I think they called it - it was under Lord Derby's, you know, yes. And we had to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Blackpool{\*\xmlclose}
 on the Monday morning. Us came home and - told me parents, you know. Well on the Saturday morning as I should have gone to Blackpool we had - I had a letter from the war office to say that I was to join the - Second First West Lancs w
ith me brothers at - Blackpool. Me brother was in that mob you see. I didn't know but apparently he claimed me and I believe at that time it was the privilege of an elder brother - I didn't know, but apparently me mother had written and told me brother th
a
t I'd joined the Army and I would join this infantry mob which of course, that was more in my line. And he apparently claimed me and he got me in as a trumpeter because I was only little fellow you see. In - in the heavy artillery you had to be about five
 foot ten before they took you in it. So - anyway, off we went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Blackpool{\*\xmlclose}. And - like then we moved from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Blackpool{\*\xmlclose}
 to - Woolwich. And there at Woolwich, from the old 4.7. guns than we had we - were equipped with a sixty pounder gun. Mater of fact we were the first Territorial battery I believe to take a sixty pounder - coach loaded gun to France.
