 overseas - the head trumpeter went as the Major's batman and - we were all - fact - as a matter of fact like the funny part about that was that in open - in Borden when we came in - under orders for overseas we were overstrength you see, so eve
rybody had to go and pass the doctor. And they were having sweepstakes upon who would pass the doctor and who wouldn't. Of course it was ten to one against me - the doctor see. But I passed the doctor and several fellows who - who like thought they were c
e
rtainties didn't - didn't pass the doctor. So we went overseas. I can't remember the date. I - next I had - dose of gas - yes. And I - I can't remember anything about it, it's very - but I remember this morning we woke up in our bivouacs you know and I wa
s tremendously sick and I - I didn't know - my stomach was terrible and I reported sick and they sent me to hospital and - it - it's all very vague you know, I can remember we were in sort of tent and they gave you a sort of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1051982\charrsid3029110 steen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 ing pipes or kettles or som
ething and I was - I don't know really how long out - out of the line down and got down to - to Etappes I think we got in the end. And - then - you went - you went before a board you know and - I was pronounced fit and I was - then I was sent to Etappes, 
that was it that was the training base. That was just outside - Etappes outside - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4087616\charrsid3029110 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Boulogne}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 {\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 I think is that. And - there I - I met a chap from Everton and we palled sort of thing and you went before a board every week. I was on - light duty because it had af
fected my heart. I had - what they call D.I.H. Disorder - D.A.H. - disorderly action of the heart. That's what I was down under like - light duty with you see. And there there was a Major in the riding school who got a very bad knee - and I remember the f
irst day I went in the riding school he - pulled the riding - the ride up and he came to me and he said, name, you know. Told him. Regiment? Told him {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West Ban}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1051982\charrsid3029110 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 s{\*\xmlclose}
 you know. He said, this man. -So he got down and he said, what you come down the line with? So I
 told him. So he said, all right, go over there he said and don't ride again. So than I got - I got on light job. Can't remember now what I was doing but I got a light job, you know, until - I got in with some chaps and we - we made an agreement the four 
o
f us that - nobody would take - you know, they used to say every day on parade - I want three volunteers for such and such a - a mob you see, and they said that we wouldn't take any posting unless the whole four went together see. But after making this pr
o
mise, two of 'em fell out and the next day they took a posting and eventually I - I was posted to the - 128 heavy company at - Leignes. I - I went up there and - I found that they were a mixture of a Wessex battery, you see, in - in the first place these 
b
atteries were four gun and then they - made us six guns you see when they - did away with Territorials. That - that meant that the - see in the Territorials I was 1799 but when they - when they went over to this new organisation my number became 308984 se
e, we were sort of regulars. And I went up to this company with this lad and we - we - we settled in so very nice. I always remember the captain was chap named Mead and at that time the Hapshire }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4087616\charrsid3029110 captain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110  at cricket was a man named Mead. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Philip Mead?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 That's right - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 He went blind later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Did he? Oh - I don't know. Well in - there - we - we did all right there until - one night - I was detailed to take ammunition up the line. It wasn't a bad night but the corporal said to me, the
re's a horse there on the lines, he said, it's been on the sick list but it hasn't been out, he said, for months, he said, will you take that? Of course I took this fresh hourse you know. So of course when the bombardment started in the front of course th
e
 horse didn't like it. Well that - the next - I woke up with - they'd picked me up like and carried me to a place and they'd got - two R.A.M.C. fellows I think they were the first night. Vague this was you know. And then - the next thing I - I know is tha
t
 - I'm back in the bivouac - we were in a barn up - attached an old farm and - I there - pal with two - cockneys. Now cockneys get a bad name don't they but these were two - two chaps name Phillips, brothers they were. And they were looking after me as I 
- was then bandaged up and that you know. And in the end they said, look - we don't like this. We're going to see }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1051982\charrsid3029110 Mead}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 . See. So I said, it's up to you. So they went and saw him and they brought the captain to me and he looked at me and he said to them, turn
 out the gig. We had a little gig there. With one horse you see - and he packed me off to hospital. Well - it was to - to a clear - to a field - to a depot first you see. When the - corporal there saw me he gave me a - the needle you - know. And then I la
y
 a while and he gave me a cigarette - I remember this - and - this officer, the doctor came you see and he just pulled the bandages away and looked at the - they'd all - they were all septic you see the wounds and that so he just said something to them. N
ext thing I knew I was being carried off and that - night I was put on to a train and came down to - some blooming place - forgetting - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Rouen{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Aye. I always remember this because as they carried us off the train the - I suppose the - transport was lined up 
you know, and these two chaps carried me off and this receiving officer just looked at the - label on the coat and he said to - thirteen general. Always remember that. Don't know - and I thought, oh - thirteen - unlucky you know. It turned out to be an Am
e
rican hospital manned by American ladies it was and - they were really very nice there. And I was there I think two days and then there was - a tremendous push on the western front and they were coming in, oh, you know, and - so she said to me, this after
n
oon - do you think you could get up? I said, I think so. So she said, well get up and then - get downstairs and the porter will help you - pick up your belongings, she said, and I can put you on a boat this afternoon, as a walking patient. It was full up 
w
ith stretcher cases but she said I can put you on as a walking patient. And I remember this day. We - were put onto the boat you know and the - we sat there until it went a little dusk then we came over the channel with destroyers on each side. Eventually
 I finished at Aldershot.
