me - Be that man he said, get in the lead. So I had to be on the lead horses you see. Well I was on the wheel when I went up so we - he gave us the signal, we went up you know, we galloped up and I said, yah, pull up, you know and - the - immediately he -
 
he go - waah he said. He came up to me, he said, what - what Regiment? I said, 21 Lancs, Sir. He said to the fellows see, see that - that's how it's done he said to me. He swore - he said, bugger off, he said. Don't want to see you any more. I went in the
 
Y.M.C.A. for the rest of the day. I - I got through very well, well then I got down to that and I - first of all I struck up - a terrible part - opposition I should say, to a young Lieutenant named Melville. He was about nineteen and they do say that his 
p
arents had bought him this conscription but they were very well off people. His father and mother used to come in a chauffeur driven limousine to see him at times and although we hit it off badly at first afterwards we hit it off very well and he asked me
 
would I be his groom. Look after his horse and his - see, and he paid me about five and six a week and - I remember - of course it was good pay you see, I was only on one and tuppence a day in - in the Army. And - any - anything I wanted I only just had t
o
 say to my Mr Molville, there's no polish or there's no - saddle soap you see and he - he'd pay it without question. And - then - then a funny thing happened. The - the chap who was the battery orderly had been in the Ter - Terriers you know and had been 
a
ll through - and it was now about 1917 - back end I think and he'd never been overseas and so the - the dictum went out that everybody had to be cleared you see. So of course when this chap went he - the Gold Watch Sergeant Major said, anybody here a cler
k
? This was on the morning parade you know. Nobody answered. Anybody been a clerk? Nobody answered. Anybody been a clerk? Nobody answered. Did none of you do it, he said. So I stopped forward. He said, have you done? I said, no, I said, but - I said, I thi
n
k I', clever enough to do the job. He said all right fall out. So became and showed me the battery and I you know, run the whole system then you see and - so it was - were in the captain and in charge of the lads was a man named Smith, a Welshman. He was 
a
 great horseman and - we - I had remarkable fine time there with them until the end of the war came you know and - he went on strike. They wouldn't do any more parades. So it - it got a bit awkward you see because I was - very well in with the chaps you k
n
ow and the - I worked for. There was also very up in the officers you see and I didn't want to strike and I didn't want to have to show side but - the men very gallantly said to me, now you're all right. When we go on parade in the morning you - you blow 
p
arade just as usual, the whistle you know, and - we're not coming out. So that was all right. I just came and I thought - there was the Sergeant Major and myself. I'd blowen the parade and no men. And they walked through Winchester, they protested you kno
w
, but - in the end the - one fellow got his cards, they said he was a bit mad and he led - you know, but - the - eased the position a bit you know as regards things. He was a fellow that didn't take interest in training 'cos the war was over. Yes. And the
n
 about - a couple of days after that like there came an officer in - in there and I was talking to him and he said to me, something about civil life, you know. And I said I was with Crawfords. Ohh, he said, I was a commercial traveler used to call at Craw
f
ords, he said, I know them very well. And - well - he - he told me to write to Crawfords and he'd vouch for it and - write to Crawfords and they'd claim me back and I'd get out the Army. Come back - like you know, very early in November - in 1920 I was ba
ck home -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 1919 - because the war finished in 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
That's right. It would be 1919 then. Yes. I know I was one of the first back at the works.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Would you have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Yes. I - I think so. In the first place,
 yes, but after I got into Crawrords and and got into working, no, it was just my ideal. And - and I - as I said to Mr - to Mr Archie like - I - I gave me - it was only to studying the thing and to learning the job you know and - I didn't fail anything, s
ee. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 You didn't serve an apprenticeship did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Or a training period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 You didn't belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Did you feel that employers and workers and the same interests or different ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
That's - well its difference isn't it because you know, human nature being as it is the majority of fellows always thought the employer was a bad man didn't he. Yes. More or less. I - I think more or less the employers - employers always thought the em
ployees -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 What did you think yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Oh I was very satisfied personally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 You thought they had the same or different interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
I - I thought they were very interested in you. In fact I - I held this view of Crawfords whether I was r
ight or wrong - but I had this view of Crawfords, that if ever anything had happened I think I could have gone to them and said, look I'm in a spot of bother, could you help me? And they'd have helped me. In fact I know like of one fellow who was concerne
d in - in a court case in there and they got him away with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Did you feel there were divisions of interest among the workers themselves? Some people say in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers - did you feel this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Oh yes, I think - I think that was so. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Would you say that full time work changed your attitude to life in any way?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Oh no, I think it - I think it increased my - because - I went through - through my years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Not a bit and I - I - I would like here to say that - sometime back you asked me did we have any set h
ours like at home and I - I - recall now - I thought about it after we spoke last time that - until I joined the Army I had to be in by half past nine of an evening unless I had permission. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 No. No. Not until - joined the Army - not until I joined the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you go out in the evenings after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Oh yes, like with the - you know - these associations.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Is that all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Yes. I think - after I - coming home, of course that's after - you don't want after 1918 do you. No. Up til then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you make any new friends - boys or girls at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 I all - I think your friends in with t
he Boys Brigade teams often you see because when - when a boys reach seventeen it was up to the boy - if he was that type he - he kept on with us. If he wasn't he left us and probably wandered off and - probably was on some other sphere that we'd meet him
. But, you see, my interest was always in that and I became the Secretary of the - mens council and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Did you ever bring your friends home?
