\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 What jobs did you have to do at home for your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
At home? Well my - my particular job would be to get in at night chips and coal ready for lighti
ng the fire next morning you know and - I would very probably during the daytime have to take care of the younger children like below me you know, take them out and I also had to do evening work you know. I - I did - I did - before I left school, let's se
e
, I did one - for a near neighbour who had the newsagents business - I used to take papers in the evening to a club in Old Swan. And then - later on like, my elder brother was working at a shop in Prescott Road, I used to go down and stand in the doorway 
a
nd when he went on an errand I would go with him until in the end, Mr Dobbs was the man's name, the boss, he, this Saturday evening he must have been a very observant man and must have known I was doing this and he called me into the shop this evening you
 see and said - I was on the staff sort of business from that time and paid me something - it was only about one and ninepence a week I got for this job you know. And that was my first -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 I meant the jobs you had at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7157778 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 The jobs I used to have - I used to have to cut the Echo out for toilet paper.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8401235 TC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4223140\charrsid3029110 
Ah well, not - see there was more probably in our family than yours - so many of us. But they're the sort of things I used to have to do - get the chips and coal in and - and clean the s
hoes and take the other children out. And - and of course run errands you know - if you remember at that time the Maypole was first coming upon the scene and we used to go all the way from here, Rathbone Road to Kensington to the Maypole to get -
